FIFA DreamTeam

Tlotliso Jonas & Matthew Roberts

04/07/2020

Project Description

The aim of the project was to a use data driven approach to build a budget constrained, winning soccer team using the relationship between player statistics and their value. Three teams will be created, the first one with a limited budget of 500 millions, the second one with the budget limit of 700 millions and the third unconstrained team. Additionally, we have created our own team layout and thus have selected our players so to fit this layout and have players on the bench. The three teams will then be compared on their overall ratings and total value of the team.

We have first cleaned the data set, then examined the relationship and distributions between variables. Thereafter we have analyzed various regression methods as well as breaking down and understanding the player characteristics We have then used the regression model and characteristics we deemed most suitable to value the players. Finally we have created the constrained and unconstrained teams.

It can be noted that the Value and Wage column have a strange format and will not be useful in numeric operations later if they have that format. In the code below we write a function and use it to clean up these two columns.

#A function for cleaning wage and value columns
fix_value<-function(value){
  clean_value<-str_remove(value,"")
  if (str_detect(clean_value,"M"))
  {
     clean_value<-as.numeric(str_remove(clean_value,"M"))*1e6    
  }
  else if (str_detect(clean_value,"K"))
  {
     clean_value<-as.numeric(str_remove(clean_value,"K"))*1e3 
  }
  return (clean_value)
}

#Clean the wage and value columns
data$Value<-as.numeric(lapply(data$Value,fix_value)) 
data$Wage<-as.numeric(lapply(data$Wage,fix_value))

Data Understanding

We analyze different aspects of the data by plotting distributions of variables:

Preferred Foot

From the plot above it can be seen that most fifa players are right footed and there are also very few players who do not have foot preference.

Age Distribution

From the age distribution above it can be observed that most fifa players are between 20 to 25 years of age and it can also be noted that the youngest player is 16 years old while the oldest is 45 years old. This may form an important aspect of the team selection so to strengthen the longevity of the team.

Positions Distributions

In this plot we observe the number of players per position and it can be noted that some positions such as goalkeeping and striker have a lot of players while other positions such as left forward and right forward are being played by very few players. This may result in a better estimation of value where the sample size is larger.

Wage Distribution

From the wage distribution above we can see that almost all the players earn about just less than 250 000 euros and very few players earn above 500 000 euros.

Value Distribution

Here we observe that there are some players that do not have any value associated with no value and this might be the free agent players and we also observe that most players are valued in millions with most players being valued less that 20 million euros. The presence of these zero valued players will be an important consideration when doing the regression.

Number of Skill Moves of Players Distribution

Here we observe that most players have 2 and 3 skill moves while very few players have 5 skill moves

Speciality Score Distribution

The speciality score displays the right skewness normal distribution behavior. Here we observe that most players have the speciality score of about 1600 to 1800.

Player Overall Rating Distribution

From the player overall rating distribution above, the first thing that can be noted is that the player overall ratings are symmetrically skewed.It can also be observed that most players have an overall rating of about 68% to 70% and very few players are rated more than 90%.

Player Potential Rating Distribution

Here we can observe that player potential rating have the a very similar distribution to that of the player overall rating distribution.

Model Investigation

Project AIM

As mentioned earlier the aim of the project is to build teams using statistical analysis. In this section we investigate different regression methods to find a method that offers the strongest relationship with the data and one that will best value players. We have made use of only positive player value so to limit the potential skew brought in my zero value players.

The first approach was the standard linear regression. The models coefficients were highly significant shown in their low P-values, however in comparison with the other models the \(R^2\) value was low. Additionally, looking at the plot of fitted vs actual value, we see the model gave very high values to some of the lower valued players. This may suggest the model is not as accurate as desired.

Our second method made use of the log of the player value. We did this in an attempt to put the data on a more relative scale. This would mean a small difference in rating would not correspond to such large changes in value. This method seems to have worked well with all coefficients significant and a high \(R^2\) at 0.888. When looking at the relationship between the fitted and actual player values, we however see the same over valuation at the lower price points. Without the analysis of these fitted points this model may have been the best option had we only focused on the \(R^2\) and the significant coefficients.

Next we tried to scale up the ratings to put them on an equal scale to the player values. This was done by finding the relationship between the average of the sum of all Player Overall and Potential ratings to the average player value. This corresponded to putting the sum of the potential and ratings to the power of 2.9. The result of this approach was positive as we see a significantly high \(R^2\) value of 0.779 with all coefficients significant. The final test of the fitted vs actual value however gave the same result as the previous two methods. The outcome of this test gave a similar result to taking the log of the value in approach two. In hindsight this is likely due to both approaches aiming to equalize the scales of the dependent and independent variables.

Our final approach was an off shoot of approach three. We messed around with the value of the power to see if we could improve the correlation between value and whichever independent variable we chose. We finally found a value of 15 to result in the best correlation with player value. Increments either side of this figure resulted in a decrease in the correlation. This method does have low coefficients due to the size of the independent variable in comparison to the other methods, however the fit seemed to be the best. Looking at the \(R^2\) it was extremely high at 0.9416 which initially was a cause for concern for us.

Analyzing the fitted vs actual values, there seemed to be a much more linearity between the data sets which may explain the high \(R^2\). We were under the impression that the more linear the relationship in the QQ-Plot, the better the fit of the model as the fitted value more closely resembled the actual value. As a final measure, we compared the residuals of the final model which seemed to give a much better fit than the previous three models. The slight dispersion near zero is a result of the greater dispersion in value at the higher end as the data is arranged in descending order. We did not believe this dispersion was a cause for concern as we believed it may help us find some undervalued players later on in the process.

Data Analysis:

Our initial approach to understanding the data was to read up about data that we were given and try and understand how these ratings had been created. Looking at the overall and potential ratings we noticed that these ratings were already a weighted sum of the most important characteristics for that players position. This intrigued us and we tried to create our own weighting system so we could value players based on traits/skills that we believed were important. Unfortunately we found that using a combination of overall and potential ratings still gave the strongest correlation between player value and rating.

Taking this into account, we decided our default approach was to model the relationship between a combination of potential and overall versus player value. We still however wanted to test whether we could isolate characteristics that were important to each position and thus we set out comparing the standard multi-regression model of position specific characteristics against our linear regression of value and the overall/potential combination.

We have broken down the various positions into forwards, midfielders, backs and the goal keeper. We have then determined the various characteristics we believe are most important to each of these positions. From here we analyzed the correlation that each of these characteristics had with the positions player value. Important to note that again we only used players whos value was not zero to limit the impact of a skewed regression.

From here we determined which of these isolated characteristic correlations with player value were significant within the set of correlations. We created a combined player value correlation metric using the significant characteristics and tested it against our combined overall and potential metric. This gave us the first insight into whether our method would offer a better valuation model compared to the position characteristics model.

From here we computed a multiple regression using these significant correlation characteristics. We took the approach that we would go back and adjust the regression for insignificant coefficients should they arise in the initial regression. Any independent variables that were not significant at the 5% level were removed from the regression. There were a few occasions where the characteristics correlation with value was significant, however it was insignificant in the initial regression and thus was removed.

Looking at the plot of the fitted vs actual values, the second regression gives a much clearer linear relationship, corroborated by the higher correlation value between fitted and residual values. Finally, the residuals show the same dispersion around the higher values however they are much more consistent than the characteristic regression. We again are happy with this dispersion as we would ideally like to find players that are not at their fair value.

Model Development And Player Selection

In this section we have created a function that makes use of our preferred regression method and the combination of overall and potential ratings to find the value of the players. The value calculated is called the fair value of the players which is then compared to their book value to determine who is under or over valued.

Model Development

In this section we develop two functions, one for selecting top 10 undervalued players for a given the position and another one for selecting top 10 overvalued players for a given a position.

#A function to select undervalued players
undervalued<-function(position){
  cols<-c('ID','Name','Overall','Potential','Value','Position')
  pos<-filter(data[cols],Position==position)
  z<-(pos$Potential+pos$Overall)^15
  if (cor(z,pos$Value)<0.94) 
  {
    return ('Correlation is below 0.94')
  }else
  {
    pos$x<-z
    fit<-pos%>%
      lm(pos$Value ~ pos$x,data=.)
    
    coefs<-fit$coefficients
    
    players<-pos%>%mutate(fair_value=coefs[1]+coefs[2]*x)%>%
      filter(Value<fair_value)%>%
      top_n(10,Value)%>%
      select(-x)
    return (players)
  }
  
}
#A function to select overvalued players
overvalued<-function(position){
  cols<-c('ID','Name','Overall','Potential','Value','Position')
  pos<-filter(data[cols],Position==position)
  z<-(pos$Potential+pos$Overall)^15
  if (cor(z,pos$Value)<0.94) 
  {
    return ('Correlation is below 0.94')
  }else
  {
    pos$x<-z
    fit<-pos%>%
      lm(pos$Value ~ pos$x,data=.)
    
    coefs<-fit$coefficients
    
    players<-pos%>%mutate(fair_value=coefs[1]+coefs[2]*x)%>%
      filter(Value>fair_value)%>%
      top_n(10,Value)%>%
      select(-x)
    return (players)
  }
  
}

Teams Construction

In this section we use all use all the undervalued players above and use optimization technique to construct the first two constrained teams. Each team will have 20 players to play an attacking tactic and this formation is split by positions as follows:

  1. Goalkeeper(GK) - 2

  2. Defense (LB, RB, 3 X CB, RWB, LWB) - 7

  3. Midfield (CAM, CM, LDM, RDM, LCM, RCM) - 6

  4. Forward (ST, CF, LW, RW) - 5

Team 1

The code below uses r linear programming to select 20 players by maximizing the team overall and such that total value of the players is less or equal 500 million euros.

#combine all undervalued players into a single datafram
undervalue_players<-arrange(unique(rbind(ust,ucf,ulw,urw,ucam,ucm,uldm,urdm,ulcm,urcm,ulb,urb,ucb,urwb,ulwb,ugk,ulcb,urcb,ucdm,ulf)),desc(-ID))

molten_data<-melt(undervalue_players,id.vars = c('ID','Name'),value.name = 'Position',measure.vars = 'Position')
#create a constrain matrix (i.e. position constraints)
constraint_matrix<-acast(molten_data,Position ~ ID,fun.aggregate = length,value.var = 'Name' )

#get the number of positions
npos<-nrow(constraint_matrix)
#add value row to the constraint matrix (for the value constrain)
constraint_matrix<-rbind(constraint_matrix,Value=undervalue_players$Value)
#set the constraints direction per row
constraint_dir<-c(rep("==",npos),"<=")
#set the limit bounds 
constraint_limit<-c(rep(1,npos),500e6)
#solve using linear programming
lp_solution<-lp(direction = 'max',undervalue_players$Overall,constraint_matrix,constraint_dir,constraint_limit,all.int = T,transpose.constraints = T)

#The selected team
team1<-undervalue_players%>%
  filter(lp_solution$solution==1)%>%
  arrange(desc(Overall))

Conclusion

From the results of this project, it can also be noted how powerful statistics driven approach is in player valuation as we were able to use regression models to identify undervalued players and r linear programming technique to construct teams for given constraints.

In this section we give a brief comparison on the three constructed teams. When comparing the two constrained teams, the most obvious difference is that the extra 200 millions budget in team 2 was able to improve the team rating from 84.55% to 86.05% and this meant that only 7 players had to change as 13 players didnt change. In team2 there exist some highly rated players such as Ronaldo but the overall player rating doesnt vary that much in both teams is about the same.

The unconstrained team has the highest overall team rating than all the teams as expected, even though this rating not significantly different from the two constrained teams we can however note that there was a overshoot in the total value (1.12 billion euros) of the team as the was no value constrain in this team. Since the unconstrained team consisted of about 11 undervalued players, one other factor that can be useful to investigate is the overall rating and the total value of the optimum team where the optimum team can be constructed by constructing a number of teams using a technique that minimizes the budget and maximize the team overall rating.
